video_description: The U.S. finally got a national bird. Government websites called bald eagles the national bird. Textbooks and newspaper articles agreed. But when Preston Cook searched high and low for any official documentation cementing the birdâ€™s status, he found nothing. Flabbergasted, in 2011 he wrote to his senator â€” the late Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat from California â€” asking if her staff could investigate this mystery at the National Archives. â€œIt turns out that the documentation wasnâ€™t missing â€” it didnâ€™t exist. Weâ€™ve never had a national bird,â€ Cook told The Washington Post. â€œThe senator sent me back a letter saying itâ€™sÂ assumedÂ to be our national bird, but it has never been declared our national bird.â€ On Monday, Congress made it official. The bald eagle will become the national bird after 248 years. Caption from article by Maria Luisa Paul.

Where did we get syphilis? In a study published Wednesday in the journalÂ Nature, an international team studied ancient DNA harvested from lesion-ridden bones or teeth of five people who lived in Peru, Chile, Argentina and Mexico either before or around the time of Columbus. They found that early versions of the microbe,Â Treponema pallidum,Â that causes syphilis and related diseases were already diverse and widespread. Their analysis suggests that syphilis emerged in the Americas within the last 8,000 years and spread across the globe fueled by European colonization. â€œThe syphilis debate was a big one, and it was a very emotional one ... a famous paleopathologist described it as one of the most enigmatic questions in science,â€ said Kirsten Bos, group leader for molecular paleopathology at the Max Planck Institute for Evolutionary Anthropology and one of the leaders of the work. She argued the new evidence would settle the matter. â€œItâ€™s a very clear slam dunk: Okay, this clearly came from the Americas.â€ Several outside researchers agreed the study provides valuable new evidence strongly suggesting an American origin for syphilis, but added that it wouldnâ€™t close the debate. Understanding the differences between the subspecies that cause these different, but related, diseases is a key question for scientists trying to understand these diseases today. Caption from article by Carolyn Y. Johnson.

FTC MAKES sellers REVEAL â€œjunk fees" The Federal Trade Commission on Tuesday issued long-awaited rules requiring companies to display the full price of a hotel room, concert ticket or sporting event up front to customers, rather than hiding any extra charges â€” often called â€œjunk feesâ€ â€” until the very end of the checkout process.The new regulations, which are slated to take effect next year, seek to crack down on â€œbait and switchâ€ pricing practices, according to FTC Chair Lina Khan, who said the agency has received a groundswell of complaints about service charges, amenity fees and a raft of other potentially obscure, last-minute additions to consumersâ€™ bills. The FTCâ€™s rules still allow companies to impose fees, so long as they are clearly displayed.The agency also focused its prohibition on just the lodging and live-event industries, not the fuller array of firms â€” from airlines to internet giants â€” that have similarly stoked public anger.

Young adults are far more likely to approve of Luigi Mangione. The pollster YouGov askedÂ a battery of questionsÂ recently about the killing of UnitedHealthcare chief executive Brian Thompson in Manhattan two weeks ago and the man who has been charged for it, Luigi Mangione. (Mangione wasÂ charged Tuesday with murder and terrorism.) Many people appeared unfamiliar with the story, offering no opinions. But among those who did, lots of young adults appeared sympathetic toward the alleged killer. And notably, they perceived those around them as sharing such views. The poll, which surveyed more than 1,000 people, showed Americans adults under 30 are about evenly split on whether they view Mangione favorably or unfavorably. About one-third hold each view. Adults aged 30 to 44 leaned only slightly negatively toward him. (In contrast, Americans aged 65-plus viewed Mangione unfavorably by about a 15-to-1 margin. Overall, Americans viewed Mangione more than 2-to-1 negatively.) Younger adults actually viewed Mangione more favorably than the man he allegedly killed, Thompson. Caption from article by Aaron Blake.

Reality TV contestants may soon be employees. The National Labor Relations Board said this week that contestants on the show â€œLove Is Blindâ€ are employees and should have the work protections that come with that classification. Once remedied, the caseÂ could become the basis for the improved working conditions that reality show stars have long awaited. After the agency worked with two â€œLove Is Blindâ€ stars who filed unfair labor practice chargesÂ in 2023, the NLRB regional office in Minnesota assigned to the case issued a filing Wednesday. It said the hit Netflix showâ€™s production companies â€” Delirium TV and Kinetic Content â€” had misclassified contestants as â€œnon-employee â€˜participantsâ€™â€ and found that they had required cast mates to sign participant agreements to discourage them from participating in legally protected labor actions, such as unionizing. The production companies and their former employees must come to an agreement on remedies due to the unlawful portions of the contract or meet for a hearing before an NLRB judge on April 22. Caption from original article by Samantha Chery.

Itâ€™s the most volcanically active world in our solar neighborhood, and has an impressive rÃ©sumÃ© for a place that is only slightly larger than our own moon.â€œIo is one of the most intriguing objects in the whole solar system,â€ said Scott Bolton, a director at the Southwest Research Institute. â€œThis body is completely covered with volcanoes over both poles, all across its middle, constantly going off. learned about his parents how he grew up he went to Cornell then he went to Juilliard here he met Robin Williams they had a lifelong friendship boom he's hired for Superman the hottest Clark Kent he's filming in London where he meets Gae Exton they begin a relationship because his parentsâ€™ relationship was not a great example Christopher could not commit but he was living in London with Gae together they had two children son Matthew and daughter Alexandra Christopher is busier and busier doing Superman's 1 2 3 and 4 in 1987 Gae and Christopher decide to separate he moves back to the US and he sees his children on holidays later that same year Christopher meets a young singer actress named Dana Morosini they were a couple living together but again Christopher had commitment issues Christopher was Superman he was 6â€™4 buff athletic very physical he was a pilot he wind surfed sailed boats he learned how to ride horses for a project he was in even though he was allergic after about five years Christopher finally decided to propose to Dana and they got married in 1992 later that same year they had a son they named William in this documentary they talk about the tragic accident that happened in 1995 he was competing at a horse show when right before the third jump his horse just refused completely stopped Christopher was thrown off the horse fell directly on his head broken snapped just like a noose half an inch to the left he would have been gone half an inch to the right he would have just gotten up his first and second vertebrae completely destroyed his
